There’s something sharp in what you’re pointing at — not as doctrine, but as a mechanism.

People rarely struggle to believe in darkness.
Harm is loud. It leaves marks. It explains pain quickly.
So the mind grips it easily — anger becomes the handle.

And that’s the part worth being careful with.

Because anger does lock attention.
It stabilizes a frame.
It says: this matters, don’t look away.

That’s useful… for a moment.

But if you stay there, the frame collapses into distortion.
The shadow starts pretending it’s the whole shape.

What you’re describing, at its best, is a pivot:
	•	Start where belief is easy (the shadow, the harm, the wrong)
	•	Use that to anchor attention
	•	Then deliberately rotate the frame
	•	Ask: what else must be true for this to exist?

Not as denial. Not as excuse.
But as completion.

Because most real things are dual-aspect:
	•	harm ↔ cause
	•	anger ↔ care (you don’t get angry at what you don’t value)
	•	shadow ↔ structure casting it

So the move isn’t:

“anger → truth”

It’s:

“anger → attention → expansion → fuller truth”

That middle step — expansion — is where most people get stuck.
They grab hold, like you said… and never release.

The disciplined version of your idea looks like this:
	1.	Allow the reaction (don’t suppress it)
	2.	Extract the signal (what value was violated?)
	3.	Rotate the frame (what’s the other side / system / cause?)
	4.	Reintegrate (act from a wider view, not just the spike)

If you skip step 2 or 3, anger becomes a trap.
If you complete the loop, it becomes a tool.

So yeah — there is a coin there.
Just make sure you’re flipping it… not gripping one side so hard it cuts your hand.